05516nam a22007575i 9780691194554DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911945547 a10.1515/97806911945542doi  a(DE-B1597)544513  a(OCoLC)1134854794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aARC0050802bisacsh1 aStanek, Łukasz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArchitecture in Global Socialism :bEastern Europe, West Africa, and the Middle East in the Cold War /cŁukasz Stanek. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b150 color + 127 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter 1. Introduction: Worldmaking of Architecture -- tChapter 2. A Global Development Path Accra, 1957-66 -- tChapter 3. Worlding Eastern Europe Lagos, 1966-79 -- tChapter 4. The World Socialist System Baghdad, 1958-90 -- tChapter 5. Socialism within Globalization Abu Dhabi and Kuwait City, 1979-90 -- tEpilogue and Outlook -- tA Note on Sources -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tImage Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow socialist architects, planners, and contractors worked collectively to urbanize and develop the Global South during the Soviet eraIn the course of the Cold War, architects, planners, and construction companies from socialist Eastern Europe engaged in a vibrant collaboration with those in West Africa and the Middle East in order to bring modernization to the developing world. Architecture in Global Socialism shows how their collaboration reshaped five cities in the Global South: Accra, Lagos, Baghdad, Abu Dhabi, and Kuwait City.Łukasz Stanek describes how local authorities and professionals in these cities drew on Soviet prefabrication systems, Hungarian and Polish planning methods, Yugoslav and Bulgarian construction materials, Romanian and East German standard designs, and manual laborers from across Eastern Europe. He explores how the socialist development path was adapted to tropical conditions in Ghana in the 1960s, and how Eastern European architectural traditions were given new life in 1970s Nigeria. He looks at how the differences between socialist foreign trade and the emerging global construction market were exploited in the Middle East in the closing decades of the Cold War. Stanek demonstrates how these and other practices of global cooperation by socialist countries-what he calls socialist worldmaking-left their enduring mark on urban landscapes in the postcolonial world.Featuring an extensive collection of previously unpublished images, Architecture in Global Socialism draws on original archival research on four continents and a wealth of in-depth interviews. This incisive book presents a new understanding of global urbanization and its architecture through the lens of socialist internationalism, challenging long-held notions about modernization and development in the Global South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArchitecturezAfrica, West. 0aArchitecturezEurope, Eastern. 0aArchitecturezMiddle East. 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eB